{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2024-01-03","name":"Miles de Courcy 1st Baron Kingsale","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Miles de Courcy 1st Baron Kingsale","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Miles"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Courcy"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":"1st Baron Kingsale"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1288–Male","fullLifespan":"1288–","birthDate":"+1288","birthPlace":{"address":"Kinsale, County Cork, Ireland","geo":{"latitude":51.7087,"longitude":-8.522,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\nMiles de Courcy was summoned for service against the Scots in 1310 and 1335\n\nHe served as Sheriff of Cork 1329-32\n\nMiles de Courcy, first Baron Kingsale; created 1st Baron Kinsale by writ of summons about 1339/40\n\nfrom Cracroft's Peerage - Miles [de Courcy] 1st Baron Kinsale as born somewhere about 1286. He married Joanna; and had died before the 6th December 1344.\n\nMiles, the son of John De Courcy, succeeded his father as the sixth Lord of Kingsale. Miles de Courcy was 5th or 6th in succession according to the list provided by the \"Complete Peerage\".\n\nMiles de Courcy was present in the Parliament, holden at Dublin with King Edward III of England sitting as the first Baron of the kingdom of Ireland. He was summoned by King Edward in 1344, to bring ten men at arms and thirty hobelars (light cavalry) to Portsmouth, England, to take part in a punitive campaign against King Philippe VI of France for his breach of the truce between the kingdoms of France and England. Edward III had established relatively amicable relations with Philippe, until Philippe provided refuge for King David ll of Scotland in 1334 which enraged Edward lll, though Edward did openly declare war on France at the time.\n\nAfter his return from France, he campaigned against Florence MacCarthy Mór (Finghin, the son of Cormac McCarthy Mór), winning a battle near Ring-Rone, and driving them into the river of Bandon, where Florence MacCarthy and many of his men were drowned.\n\nBy Johanna his wife (who survived him) he had three sons.\nMiles, the eldest, became the seventh Lord Kingsale & married Honora O'Brien\nthe two youngest were slain in 1339, with David de Courcy and other nobles","events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1288","date":"1288","place":"Kinsale, County Cork, Ireland"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1315","date":"1315","place":"Kingsdale, Cork, Ireland","age":"27","id":"GXCD-57S"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1318","date":"1318","place":"Kinsale, County Cork, Ireland","age":"30","id":"GNPJ-ZVY"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1320","date":"1320","place":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","age":"32","id":"G67K-4HV"},{"name":"Death","sources":"0"}],"parent":[{"name":"John De Courcy","gender":"Male","lifespan":"–1301","deathDate":"+1301","@type":"Person","identifier":"L77D-9TL","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/L77D-9TL/john-de-courcy-1301","published":true},{"name":"Joan Roche","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1248–Female","birthDate":"+1248","@type":"Person","identifier":"GNWT-QCH","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GNWT-QCH/joan-roche-1248","published":true}],"sibling":[{"name":"Miles de Courcy 1st Baron Kingsale","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1288–Male","birthDate":"+1288","@type":"Person","identifier":"GK12-Z4D","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GK12-Z4D/miles-de-courcy-1st-baron-kingsale-1288","published":true}],"spouse":[{"name":"Joan de Cogan","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1291–1344","birthDate":"+1291","deathDate":"+1344","age":53,"@type":"Person","identifier":"GNW2-Q7R","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GNW2-Q7R/joan-de-cogan-1291-1344","published":true}],"children":[{"name":"Edmund de Courcy","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1315–1344","birthDate":"+1315","deathDate":"+1344","age":29,"otherParentId":"GNW2