me":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Courcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Andree, Jacques, Michel, Monique.","French: habitational name from any of the places in Calvados, Loiret, Manche, and Marne called Courcy.","History: Nicolas Lemière <i>dit</i> Courcy from Courcy in Manche, France, married Louise-Geneviève Dubé in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1749."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Miles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Norman origin but uncertain derivation. Unlike most Norman names it is, as far as can be ascertained, not derived from any known Old French or Germanic name element. It may be a greatly altered pet form of   Michael  , which came to be associated with the Latin word <i>miles</i> ‘soldier’ because of the military attributes of the archangel Michael. However, the usual Latin form of the name in the Middle Ages was <i>Milo</i>. There is a common Slavic name element <i>mil</i> ‘grace, favour’, with which it may possibly have some connection. The name has been in regular use in England since the 16th century.  See also  Milo   and   Myles ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Miles de Courcy 1st Baron Kingsale was born in 1288, in Kinsale, County Cork, Ireland as the son of John De Courcy and Joan Roche. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Joan de Cogan."},"et":{"1288–":"1288–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1291–1344":"1291–1344","1315–1344":"1315–1344","1318–1390":"1318–1390","1320–